{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}

[[File:Japanese Crest Abe no Seimei Hann.svg|thumb|Seimei crest]]
'''Onmyōdō Sōke''' (陰陽道宗家) refers to the historical designation for the head family (宗家, ''sōke'') or head of a lineage (家元, ''iemoto'') in the practice of {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道}}. From the mid to late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}}, the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏}} and its main line {{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家 (賀茂氏)}} served as the hereditary heads of {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道}}, while the {{ill|Abe clan (Onmyōdō)|ja|阿倍氏}} and its main line {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家（安倍氏）}} held authority over {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道}}. Together, these two families were known as the "Anga Ryōke" (安賀両家). However, after the decline of the Kamo clan during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, the title "Onmyōdō Sōke" came to primarily refer to the Tsuchimikado family.

In {{ill|1870|ja|明治3年}}, following the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新}}, the new government issued the {{ill|Prohibition of Heavenly Worship Decree|ja|天社禁止令}}, abolishing Onmyōdō as superstition. Consequently, the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家（安倍氏）}} and related branches, such as the {{ill|Kurahashi family|ja|倉橋家}} and {{ill|Kōtokui family|ja|幸徳井家}}, formally ceased their involvement in Onmyōdō practices. Despite the revival of {{ill|Tensha Tsuchimikado Shintō|ja|天社土御門神道}} after World War II, the Tsuchimikado family has distanced itself from these activities. Thus, the positions of "Onmyōji" and "Onmyōdō Sōke" no longer exist in any official capacity today.

== The Kamo Clan and Kadenokōji Family ==
{{main|Kamo clan|Kadenokōji family (Kamo clan)}}
