{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}

[[File:Japanese Crest Abe no Seimei Hann.svg|thumb|Seimei crest]]
'''Onmyōdō Sōke''' (陰陽道宗家) refers to the historical designation for the head family (宗家, ''sōke'') or head of a lineage (家元, ''iemoto'') in the practice of {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft}}. From the mid to late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏|qq=draft}} and its main line {{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家 (賀茂氏)|qq=draft}} served as the hereditary heads of {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft}}, while the {{ill|Abe clan (Onmyōdō)|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft}} and its main line {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家（安倍氏）|qq=draft}} held authority over {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft}}. Together, these two families were known as the "Anga Ryōke" (安賀両家). However, after the decline of the Kamo clan during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft}}, the title "Onmyōdō Sōke" came to primarily refer to the Tsuchimikado family.

In {{ill|1870|ja|明治3rd year|qq=draft}}, following the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft}}, the new government issued the {{ill|Prohibition of Heavenly Worship Decree|ja|天社禁止令|1=Tensha Shinto Prohibition Ordinance|qq=draft}}, abolishing Onmyōdō as superstition. Consequently, the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家（安倍氏）|qq=draft}} and related branches, such as the {{ill|Kurahashi family|ja|倉橋家|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kōtokui family|ja|幸徳井家|qq=draft}}, formally ceased their involvement in Onmyōdō practices. Despite the revival of {{ill|Tensha Tsuchimikado Shintō|ja|天社土御門神道|qq=draft}} after World War II, the Tsuchimikado family has distanced itself from these activities. Thus, the positions of "Onmyōji" and "Onmyōdō Sōke" no longer exist in any official capacity today.

== The Kamo Clan and Kadenokōji Family ==
{{main|Kamo clan|Kadenokōji family (Kamo clan)}}
The Kamo clan descended from {{ill|Kamo no Tadayuki|ja|賀茂忠行|qq=draft}} and his son {{ill|Kamo no Yasunori|ja|賀茂保憲|qq=draft}}, both of whom served as heads of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft}} in the mid-Heian period and were influential figures in Onmyōdō. The Kamo clan transmitted {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft}} knowledge across generations, with the main line adopting the name "Kadenokōji" during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft}}. However, the family line became extinct between the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft}} and early Edo period.{{Efn2|See {{ill|Kamo no Ariakira|ja|賀茂在昌|qq=draft}} for details on the extinction of the Kadenokōji family.}}

A branch family, the {{ill|Kōtokui family|ja|幸徳井家|qq=draft}}, survived as a {{ill|Jige-ke|ja|地下家|1=Jigeke|2=ja|3=地下家|lt=Jigeke|qq=draft}} during the Edo period. Although they initially held the title of {{ill|Onmyō no Kami|ja|陰陽頭|qq=draft}}, they lost this position to {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuhide|ja|土御門泰福|qq=draft}} after the death of {{ill|Kōtokui Tomoden|ja|幸徳井友傳|qq=draft}}. From the mid-Edo period onward, they served as assistants in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft}}.

== The Abe Clan and Tsuchimikado Family ==
{{main|Abe clan (Onmyōdō)|Tsuchimikado family (Abe clan)}}
The Abe clan, beginning with the renowned {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft}}, was the hereditary custodian of {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft}}. The main line began using the name "Tsuchimikado" during the Muromachi period, with {{ill|Abe no Ariyo|ja|安倍有世|qq=draft}} often recognized as the first Tsuchimikado patriarch. However, some sources attribute this naming convention to {{ill|Tsuchimikado Arinobu|ja|土御門有宣|qq=draft}}.

The last male head of the Tsuchimikado family, {{ill|Tsuchimikado Noritada|ja|土御門範忠|qq=draft}} (1920–1994), was succeeded by his daughter Yoshiko Tsuchimikado (born 1959). This makes her the 34th generation descendant of Abe no Seimei and the 18th generation descendant of Tsuchimikado Arinobu.{{Efn2|For details on the lineage, see {{ill|Tsuchimikado Arinobu#Descendants|ja|土御門有脩#末裔}}.}}{{Efn2|No verified male-line descendants of Abe no Seimei are publicly documented.}}

